				\begin{document}$$\rm CO_2^ - $$\end{document}, the first and the most difficult step in CO2 activation36. However, adsorption of CO2 on Cu2O surfaces results in charge redistribution with charge transfer from the surface to adsorbed CO2 that induces CO2 polarization, and consequently the energy barrier for transient electron transfer to unoccupied states of adsorbed CO2 should reduce33, 36, 37.Fig. 5
Structure and mechanism of plasmon-induced carrier-assisted rWGS on Al@Cu2O. a Energy band diagram of Al@Cu2O for plasmon-mediated carrier generation for injection into unoccupied state of CO2 for C–O bond activation. b Schematic of plasmon-induced carrier-driven rWGS on Al@Cu2O

Adsorbed CO2 can be activated through a plasmon-induced carrier-assisted mechanism. Photogenerated carriers from LSPR excitation in general overcome the activation energy barrier and transiently populate antibonding orbitals of adsorbed CO2 creating the transient negative ion (TNI)CO2-\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
