				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\rm CO_2^ - $$\end{document}, which could subsequently relax into an excited vibrational state in the ground state by releasing the electron back to Cu2O[5]. The net result is that the photogenerated hot-carriers can deposit their energy into the vibrational mode of C–O causing vibrational excitation and C–O bond elongation. Since the unoccupied molecular orbitals of CO2 are hybridized orbitals between the C and two O orbitals, the hot-carrier transfer into these orbitals can directly facilitates C–O bond dissociation, initiating the rWGS. The remaining oxygen on the surface CuCUS atom interacts with two previously dissociated hydrogen adatoms on the surface to form water. The desorption of water should be enhanced by energetic carriers, which otherwise should adsorb dissociatively on Cu2O(111)38.
